Working with GEDI data

J Camilo Fagua and Patrick Jantz

June 2021

1. INTRODUCTION

The NASA Global Ecosystem Dynamics Investigation (GEDI) is a spaceborne lidar instrument operating onboard the International Space Station (ISS) that is collecting data since April 2019 (Dubayah et al.2020). GEDI is a waveform lidar designed for measuring vegetation structure and consist of footprint-based measurements collected between ~51.6N and ~51.6 S globally. Data coverage is limited by the ISS orbit inclination (Figure 1); this video shows why GEDI orbit footprint looks like figure 1 here.

Figure 1. GEDI orbit footprint.

It is expected that GEDI samples 4% of the Earths land surface over a nominal two year mission (Potapov et al.2020). Main objectives of the GEDI mission includes the improvement of aboveground biomass estimation of tropical and temperate forests, modeling land surface carbon budgets, and understanding the effects of vegetation structure on biodiversity.

NASA has generated products to facility the use of GEDI data to users. These data products are assigned different levels, which indicate the amount of processing that the data has undergone after collection. All products are publicly available, with the lower-level products (L1 & L2) from NASAs Land Processes Distributed Active Archive Center (LPDAAC) and the higher level (L3 & L4) from the ORNL DAAC (TABLE 1). GEDI data products have limitations for practical applications because their footprints represent point samples of a limited portion of the land area. Consequently, their integration with multispectral and SAR data time-series enables the spatiotemporal extrapolation of GEDI information for consistent multidecadal monitoring of vegetation structure. Even after GEDI integration with multispectral and SAR, sampling may not be suitable for targeting rare forest change events.

TABLE 1. GEDI products.

In this tutorial, we are going to focus in downloading, visualizing, clipping, gridding, simulating and exporting three GEDI products using the R package rGEDI (Carlos Alberto 2021): 1) GEDI L1B Geolocated waveforms product, which provides geolocated corrected and smoothed waveforms, geolocation parameters, and geophysical corrections for each laser shot for all eight GEDI beams. GEDI01_B data are created by geolocating the GEDI01_A raw waveform data. 2) GEDI L2A Elevation and Height Metrics that is a set of relative height (RH) metrics (RH2, RH04, , RH100) corresponding to the percentiles of energy return height relative to the ground (2th, 4th, , 100th). These data are based on the L2A processing algorithm to the waveform interpretation (Beck et al.2020). 3) GEDI L2B Canopy Cover and Vertical Profile Metrics product that is to extract biophysical metrics from each GEDI waveform. These metrics are based on the directional gap probability profile derived from the L1B waveform. Metrics provided include canopy cover, Plant Area Index (PAI), Plant Area Volume Density (PAVD), and Foliage Height Diversity (FHD).

We also need other five R libraries in this tutorial:

  1. rgdal: It provides access to the Geospatial Data Abstraction Library-GDAL.
  2. raster: A large compilation of functions to read, write, manipulate, analyze, and model spatial data.
  3. ggplot2: A visualization package.
  4. RStoolbox: To read raster in ggplot.
  5. rhdf5: To read .h5 files.

Let us go to start. If you do not have these libraries in the R, installed them before running the command library:

2. PROCESSING GEDI DATA

Now we are going to generate the list of GEDI data for the study area. First, we select coordinates using the limits of the study area.

STUDY_AREA
## class       : SpatialPolygonsDataFrame 
## features    : 2 
## extent      : -67.08159, -67.01984, 1.268833, 1.326955  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## crs         : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs 
## variables   : 1
## names       : Id 
## min values  :  0 
## max values  :  0
ul_lat<- 1.326955 #ymax
ul_lon<- -67.08159 #xmax
lr_lat<- 1.268833 # ymin,
lr_lon<- -67.01984 #xmax

We then define the dates to obtain the GEDI data. By using the function gedifinder, we also can get the paths of the GEDI data corresponding to a study area between specific dates.

daterange=c("2019-01-01","2019-12-31")

gLevel1B<-gedifinder(product="GEDI01_B",ul_lat, ul_lon, lr_lat, lr_lon,version="001",daterange=daterange)

You need to register at EARTHDATA here to download GEDI data. EARTHDAT is an application to access more than 33,000 earth observation data collections from NASAs EOSDIS and other international partner agencies (Figure 2).

Figure 2. EARTHDATA registration website.

Now that you are registered at EARTHDATA, you will need to provide your username and password to download GEDI data after running the function gediDownload(). You can find these GEDI data in the folder of this tutorial, so you do not need to download. We prefer to avoid the data downloading because it takes long time and the EARTHDATA server sometimes presents connection issues. But you can use these lines of code to download GEDI data for any site and dates of your interest.

You can convert level1bGeo_1 data as data.frame or SpatialPointsDataFrame. Under these formats, the GEDI data can be operated using the large sets of other R libraries. .

level1bGeo_1_sp<-SpatialPointsDataFrame(cbind(level1bGeo_1$longitude_bin0, level1bGeo_1$latitude_bin0),
                                        data=level1bGeo_1)

For instance, we can export the SpatialPointsDataFrame in a ESRI shapefile. We are not going to export the data due to the time execution. Remember that you first need to Converting shot_number as integer64 to character to export as a ESRI shapefile.

#level1bGeo_1_sp$shot_number<-paste0(level1bGeo_1_sp$shot_number)

3. SOME GEDI CALCULATIONS

Let us go to open three GEDI files corresponding to the three GEDI levels (GEDI L1B, GEDI L2A, GEDI L2B)

gedilevel1b<-readLevel1B(level1Bpath = paste0(outdir,"\\GEDI01_B_2019108080338_O01964_T05337_02_003_01_sub.h5"))
gedilevel2a<-readLevel2A(level2Apath = paste0(outdir,"\\GEDI02_A_2019108080338_O01964_T05337_02_001_01_sub.h5"))
gedilevel2b<-readLevel2B(level2Bpath = paste0(outdir,"\\GEDI02_B_2019108080338_O01964_T05337_02_001_01_sub.h5"))

We can build the GEDI full-waveform of a given pulse from GEDI Level1B data using the function getLevel1BWF.

wf <- getLevel1BWF(gedilevel1b, shot_number="19640521100108408")

We also can build a plot for the GEDI full-waveform

par(mfrow = c(2,1), mar=c(4,4,1,1), cex.axis = 1.5)
plot(wf, relative=FALSE, polygon=TRUE, type="l", lwd=2, col="forestgreen",
     xlab="Waveform Amplitude", ylab="Elevation (m)")
grid()
plot(wf, relative=TRUE, polygon=FALSE, type="l", lwd=2, col="forestgreen",
     xlab="Waveform Amplitude (%)", ylab="Elevation (m)")
grid()
